8361 TemplateSpecializationKind TSK = SpecInfo->getTemplateSpecializationKind();
8362 if (TSK == TSK_Undeclared || TSK == TSK_ImplicitInstantiation) {
8363 Specialization->setLocation(FD->getLocation());
8364 Specialization->setLexicalDeclContext(FD->getLexicalDeclContext());
8365 // C++11 [dcl.constexpr]p1: An explicit specialization of a constexpr
8366 // function can differ from the template declaration with respect to
8367 // the constexpr specifier.
8368 // FIXME: We need an update record for this AST mutation.
8369 // FIXME: What if there are multiple such prior declarations (for instance,
8370 // from different modules)?
8371 Specialization->setConstexpr(FD->isConstexpr());
8372 }
8373
8374 // FIXME: Check if the prior specialization has a point of instantiation.
8375 // If so, we have run afoul of .
8376
8377 // If this is a friend declaration, then we're not really declaring
8378 // an explicit specialization.
8379 bool isFriend = (FD->getFriendObjectKind() != Decl::FOK_None);
8380
8381 // Check the scope of this explicit specialization.
8382 if (!isFriend &&
8383 CheckTemplateSpecializationScope(*this,
8384 Specialization->getPrimaryTemplate(),
8385 Specialization, FD->getLocation(),
8386 false))
8387 return true;
8388
8389 // C++ [temp.expl.spec]p6:
8390 // If a template, a member template or the member of a class template is
8391 // explicitly specialized then that specialization shall be declared
8392 // before the first use of that specialization that would cause an implicit
8393 // instantiation to take place, in every translation unit in which such a
8394 // use occurs; no diagnostic is required.
8395 bool HasNoEffect = false;
8396 if (!isFriend &&
8397 CheckSpecializationInstantiationRedecl(FD->getLocation(),
8398 TSK_ExplicitSpecialization,
8399 Specialization,
8400 SpecInfo->getTemplateSpecializationKind(),
8401 SpecInfo->getPointOfInstantiation(),
8402 HasNoEffect))
8403 return true;
8404
8405 // Mark the prior declaration as an explicit specialization, so that later
8406 // clients know that this is an explicit specialization.
8407 if (!isFriend) {
8408 // Since explicit specializations do not inherit '=delete' from their
8409 // primary function template - check if the 'specialization' that was
8410 // implicitly generated (during template argument deduction for partial
8411 // ordering) from the most specialized of all the function templates that
8412 // 'FD' could have been specializing, has a 'deleted' definition. If so,
8413 // first check that it was implicitly generated during template argument
8414 // deduction by making sure it wasn't referenced, and then reset the deleted
8415 // flag to not-deleted, so that we can inherit that information from 'FD'.
8416 if (Specialization->isDeleted() && !SpecInfo->isExplicitSpecialization() &&
8417 !Specialization->getCanonicalDecl()->isReferenced()) {
8418 // FIXME: This assert will not hold in the presence of modules.
8419 assert(
8420 Specialization->getCanonicalDecl() == Specialization &&
8421 "This must be the only existing declaration of this specialization");
8422 // FIXME: We need an update record for this AST mutation.
8423 Specialization->setDeletedAsWritten(false);
8424 }
8425 // FIXME: We need an update record for this AST mutation.
8426 SpecInfo->setTemplateSpecializationKind(TSK_ExplicitSpecialization);
8427 MarkUnusedFileScopedDecl(Specialization);
8428 }
8429
8430 // Turn the given function declaration into a function template
8431 // specialization, with the template arguments from the previous
8432 // specialization.
8433 // Take copies of (semantic and syntactic) template argument lists.
8434 const TemplateArgumentList* TemplArgs = new (Context)
8435 TemplateArgumentList(Specialization->getTemplateSpecializationArgs());
8436 FD->setFunctionTemplateSpecialization(
8437 Specialization->getPrimaryTemplate(), TemplArgs, /*InsertPos=*/nullptr,
8438 SpecInfo->getTemplateSpecializationKind(),
8439 ExplicitTemplateArgs ? &ConvertedTemplateArgs[Specialization] : nullptr);
8440
8441 // A function template specialization inherits the target attributes
8442 // of its template. (We require the attributes explicitly in the
8443 // code to match, but a template may have implicit attributes by
8444 // virtue e.g. of being constexpr, and it passes these implicit
8445 // attributes on to its specializations.)
8446 if (LangOpts.CUDA)
8447 inheritCUDATargetAttrs(FD, *Specialization->getPrimaryTemplate());
8448
8449 // The "previous declaration" for this function template specialization is
8450 // the prior function template specialization.
8451 Previous.clear();
8452 Previous.addDecl(Specialization);
8453 return false;
8454}
8455
8456/// Perform semantic analysis for the given non-template member
8457/// specialization.
8458///
8459/// This routine performs all of the semantic analysis required for an
8460/// explicit member function specialization. On successful completion,
8461/// the function declaration \p FD will become a member function
8462/// specialization.
8463///
8464/// \param Member the member declaration, which will be updated to become a
8465/// specialization.
8466///
8467/// \param Previous the set of declarations, one of which may be specialized
8468/// by this function specialization; the set will be modified to contain the
8469/// redeclared member.
8470bool
8471Sema::CheckMemberSpecialization(NamedDecl *Member, LookupResult &Previous) {
8472 assert(!isa<TemplateDecl>(Member) && "Only for non-template members");
8473
8474 // Try to find the member we are instantiating.
8475 NamedDecl *FoundInstantiation = nullptr;
8476 NamedDecl *Instantiation = nullptr;
8477 NamedDecl *InstantiatedFrom = nullptr;
8478 MemberSpecializationInfo *MSInfo = nullptr;
8479
8480 if (Previous.empty()) {
8481 // Nowhere to look anyway.
8482 } else if (FunctionDecl *Function = dyn_cast<FunctionDecl>(Member)) {
8483 for (LookupResult::iterator I = Previous.begin(), E = Previous.end();
8484 I != E; ++I) {
8485 NamedDecl *D = (*I)->getUnderlyingDecl();
8486 if (CXXMethodDecl *Method = dyn_cast<CXXMethodDecl>(D)) {
8487 QualType Adjusted = Function->getType();
8488 if (!hasExplicitCallingConv(Adjusted))
8489 Adjusted = adjustCCAndNoReturn(Adjusted, Method->getType());
8490 // This doesn't handle deduced return types, but both function
8491 // declarations should be undeduced at this point.
8492 if (Context.hasSameType(Adjusted, Method->getType())) {
8493 FoundInstantiation = *I;
8494 Instantiation = Method;
8495 InstantiatedFrom = Method->getInstantiatedFromMemberFunction();
8496 MSInfo = Method->getMemberSpecializationInfo();
8497 break;
8498 }
8499 }
8500 }
8501 } else if (isa<VarDecl>(Member)) {
8502 VarDecl *PrevVar;
8503 if (Previous.isSingleResult() &&
8504 (PrevVar = dyn_cast<VarDecl>(Previous.getFoundDecl())))
8505 if (PrevVar->isStaticDataMember()) {
8506 FoundInstantiation = Previous.getRepresentativeDecl();
8507 Instantiation = PrevVar;
8508 InstantiatedFrom = PrevVar->getInstantiatedFromStaticDataMember();
8509 MSInfo = PrevVar->getMemberSpecializationInfo();
8510 }
8511 } else if (isa<RecordDecl>(Member)) {
8512 CXXRecordDecl *PrevRecord;
8513 if (Previous.isSingleResult() &&
8514 (PrevRecord = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(Previous.getFoundDecl()))) {
8515 FoundInstantiation = Previous.getRepresentativeDecl();
8516 Instantiation = PrevRecord;
8517 InstantiatedFrom = PrevRecord->getInstantiatedFromMemberClass();
8518 MSInfo = PrevRecord->getMemberSpecializationInfo();
8519 }
8520 } else if (isa<EnumDecl>(Member)) {
8521 EnumDecl *PrevEnum;
8522 if (Previous.isSingleResult() &&
8523 (PrevEnum = dyn_cast<EnumDecl>(Previous.getFoundDecl()))) {
8524 FoundInstantiation = Previous.getRepresentativeDecl();
8525 Instantiation = PrevEnum;
8526 InstantiatedFrom = PrevEnum->getInstantiatedFromMemberEnum();
8527 MSInfo = PrevEnum->getMemberSpecializationInfo();
8528 }
8529 }
8530
8531 if (!Instantiation) {
8532 // There is no previous declaration that matches. Since member
8533 // specializations are always out-of-line, the caller will complain about
8534 // this mismatch later.
8535 return false;
8536 }
8537
8538 // A member specialization in a friend declaration isn't really declaring
8539 // an explicit specialization, just identifying a specific (possibly implicit)
8540 // specialization. Don't change the template specialization kind.
8541 //
8542 // FIXME: Is this really valid? Other compilers reject.
8543 if (Member->getFriendObjectKind() != Decl::FOK_None) {
8544 // Preserve instantiation information.
8545 if (InstantiatedFrom && isa<CXXMethodDecl>(Member)) {
8546 cast<CXXMethodDecl>(Member)->setInstantiationOfMemberFunction(
8547 cast<CXXMethodDecl>(InstantiatedFrom),
8548 cast<CXXMethodDecl>(Instantiation)->getTemplateSpecializationKind());
8549 } else if (InstantiatedFrom && isa<CXXRecordDecl>(Member)) {
8550 cast<CXXRecordDecl>(Member)->setInstantiationOfMemberClass(
8551 cast<CXXRecordDecl>(InstantiatedFrom),
8552 cast<CXXRecordDecl>(Instantiation)->getTemplateSpecializationKind());
8553 }
8554
8555 Previous.clear();
8556 Previous.addDecl(FoundInstantiation);
8557 return false;
8558 }
8559
8560 // Make sure that this is a specialization of a member.
8561 if (!InstantiatedFrom) {
8562 Diag(Member->getLocation(), diag::err_spec_member_not_instantiated)
8563 << Member;
8564 Diag(Instantiation->getLocation(), diag::note_specialized_decl);
8565 return true;
8566 }
8567
8568 // C++ [temp.expl.spec]p6:
8569 // If a template, a member template or the member of a class template is
8570 // explicitly specialized then that specialization shall be declared
8571 // before the first use of that specialization that would cause an implicit
8572 // instantiation to take place, in every translation unit in which such a
8573 // use occurs; no diagnostic is required.
8574 assert(MSInfo && "Member specialization info missing?");
8575
8576 bool HasNoEffect = false;
8577 if (CheckSpecializationInstantiationRedecl(Member->getLocation(),
8578 TSK_ExplicitSpecialization,
8579 Instantiation,
8580 MSInfo->getTemplateSpecializationKind(),
8581 MSInfo->getPointOfInstantiation(),
8582 HasNoEffect))
8583 return true;
8584
8585 // Check the scope of this explicit specialization.
8586 if (CheckTemplateSpecializationScope(*this,
8587 InstantiatedFrom,
8588 Instantiation, Member->getLocation(),
8589 false))
8590 return true;
8591
8592 // Note that this member specialization is an "instantiation of" the
8593 // corresponding member of the original template.
8594 if (auto *MemberFunction = dyn_cast<FunctionDecl>(Member)) {
8595 FunctionDecl *InstantiationFunction = cast<FunctionDecl>(Instantiation);
8596 if (InstantiationFunction->getTemplateSpecializationKind() ==
8597 TSK_ImplicitInstantiation) {
8598 // Explicit specializations of member functions of class templates do not
8599 // inherit '=delete' from the member function they are specializing.
8600 if (InstantiationFunction->isDeleted()) {
8601 // FIXME: This assert will not hold in the presence of modules.
8602 assert(InstantiationFunction->getCanonicalDecl() ==
8603 InstantiationFunction);
8604 // FIXME: We need an update record for this AST mutation.
8605 InstantiationFunction->setDeletedAsWritten(false);
8606 }
8607 }
8608
8609 MemberFunction->setInstantiationOfMemberFunction(
8610 cast<CXXMethodDecl>(InstantiatedFrom), TSK_ExplicitSpecialization);
8611 } else if (auto *MemberVar = dyn_cast<VarDecl>(Member)) {
8612 MemberVar->setInstantiationOfStaticDataMember(
8613 cast<VarDecl>(InstantiatedFrom), TSK_ExplicitSpecialization);
8614 } else if (auto *MemberClass = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(Member)) {
8615 MemberClass->setInstantiationOfMemberClass(
8616 cast<CXXRecordDecl>(InstantiatedFrom), TSK_ExplicitSpecialization);
8617 } else if (auto *MemberEnum = dyn_cast<EnumDecl>(Member)) {
8618 MemberEnum->setInstantiationOfMemberEnum(
8619 cast<EnumDecl>(InstantiatedFrom), TSK_ExplicitSpecialization);
8620 } else {
8621 llvm_unreachable("unknown member specialization kind");
8622 }
8623
8624 // Save the caller the trouble of having to figure out which declaration
8625 // this specialization matches.
8626 Previous.clear();
8627 Previous.addDecl(FoundInstantiation);
8628 return false;
8629}
8630
8631/// Complete the explicit specialization of a member of a class template by
8632/// updating the instantiated member to be marked as an explicit specialization.
8633///
8634/// \param OrigD The member declaration instantiated from the template.
8635/// \param Loc The location of the explicit specialization of the member.
8636template<typename DeclT>
8637static void completeMemberSpecializationImpl(Sema &S, DeclT *OrigD,
8638 SourceLocation Loc) {
8639 if (OrigD->getTemplateSpecializationKind() != TSK_ImplicitInstantiation)
8640 return;
8641
8642 // FIXME: Inform AST mutation listeners of this AST mutation.
8643 // FIXME: If there are multiple in-class declarations of the member (from
8644 // multiple modules, or a declaration and later definition of a member type),
8645 // should we update all of them?
8646 OrigD->setTemplateSpecializationKind(TSK_ExplicitSpecialization);
8647 OrigD->setLocation(Loc);
8648}
8649
8650void Sema::CompleteMemberSpecialization(NamedDecl *Member,
8651 LookupResult &Previous) {
8652 NamedDecl *Instantiation = cast<NamedDecl>(Member->getCanonicalDecl());
8653 if (Instantiation == Member)
8654 return;
8655
8656 if (auto *Function = dyn_cast<CXXMethodDecl>(Instantiation))
8657 completeMemberSpecializationImpl(*this, Function, Member->getLocation());
8658 else if (auto *Var = dyn_cast<VarDecl>(Instantiation))
8659 completeMemberSpecializationImpl(*this, Var, Member->getLocation());
8660 else if (auto *Record = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(Instantiation))
8661 completeMemberSpecializationImpl(*this, Record, Member->getLocation());
8662 else if (auto *Enum = dyn_cast<EnumDecl>(Instantiation))
8663 completeMemberSpecializationImpl(*this, Enum, Member->getLocation());
8664 else
8665 llvm_unreachable("unknown member specialization kind");
8666}
8667
8668/// Check the scope of an explicit instantiation.
8669///
8670/// \returns true if a serious error occurs, false otherwise.
8671static bool CheckExplicitInstantiationScope(Sema &S, NamedDecl *D,
8672 SourceLocation InstLoc,
8673 bool WasQualifiedName) {
8674 DeclContext *OrigContext= D->getDeclContext()->getEnclosingNamespaceContext();
8675 DeclContext *CurContext = S.CurContext->getRedeclContext();
8676
8677 if (CurContext->isRecord()) {
8678 S.Diag(InstLoc, diag::err_explicit_instantiation_in_class)
8679 << D;
8680 return true;
8681 }
8682
8683 // C++11 [temp.explicit]p3:
8684 // An explicit instantiation shall appear in an enclosing namespace of its
8685 // template. If the name declared in the explicit instantiation is an
8686 // unqualified name, the explicit instantiation shall appear in the
8687 // namespace where its template is declared or, if that namespace is inline
8688 // (7.3.1), any namespace from its enclosing namespace set.
8689 //
8690 // This is DR275, which we do not retroactively apply to C++98/03.
8691 if (WasQualifiedName) {
8692 if (CurContext->Encloses(OrigContext))
8693 return false;
8694 } else {
8695 if (CurContext->InEnclosingNamespaceSetOf(OrigContext))
8696 return false;
8697 }
8698
8699 if (NamespaceDecl *NS = dyn_cast<NamespaceDecl>(OrigContext)) {
8700 if (WasQualifiedName)
8701 S.Diag(InstLoc,
8702 S.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11?
8703 diag::err_explicit_instantiation_out_of_scope :
8704 diag::warn_explicit_instantiation_out_of_scope_0x)
8705 << D << NS;
8706 else
8707 S.Diag(InstLoc,
8708 S.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11?
8709 diag::err_explicit_instantiation_unqualified_wrong_namespace :
8710 diag::warn_explicit_instantiation_unqualified_wrong_namespace_0x)
8711 << D << NS;
8712 } else
8713 S.Diag(InstLoc,
8714 S.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11?
8715 diag::err_explicit_instantiation_must_be_global :
8716 diag::warn_explicit_instantiation_must_be_global_0x)
8717 << D;
8718 S.Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::note_explicit_instantiation_here);
8719 return false;
8720}
8721
8722/// Common checks for whether an explicit instantiation of \p D is valid.
8723static bool CheckExplicitInstantiation(Sema &S, NamedDecl *D,
8724 SourceLocation InstLoc,
8725 bool WasQualifiedName,
8726 TemplateSpecializationKind TSK) {
8727 // C++ [temp.explicit]p13:
8728 // An explicit instantiation declaration shall not name a specialization of
8729 // a template with internal linkage.
8730 if (TSK == TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDeclaration &&
8731 D->getFormalLinkage() == InternalLinkage) {
8732 S.Diag(InstLoc, diag::err_explicit_instantiation_internal_linkage) << D;
8733 return true;
8734 }
8735
8736 // C++11 [temp.explicit]p3: [DR 275]
8737 // An explicit instantiation shall appear in an enclosing namespace of its
8738 // template.
8739 if (CheckExplicitInstantiationScope(S, D, InstLoc, WasQualifiedName))
8740 return true;
8741
8742 return false;
8743}
8744
8745/// Determine whether the given scope specifier has a template-id in it.
8746static bool ScopeSpecifierHasTemplateId(const CXXScopeSpec &SS) {
8747 if (!SS.isSet())
8748 return false;
8749
8750 // C++11 [temp.explicit]p3:
8751 // If the explicit instantiation is for a member function, a member class
8752 // or a static data member of a class template specialization, the name of
8753 // the class template specialization in the qualified-id for the member
8754 // name shall be a simple-template-id.
8755 //
8756 // C++98 has the same restriction, just worded differently.
8757 for (NestedNameSpecifier *NNS = SS.getScopeRep(); NNS;
8758 NNS = NNS->getPrefix())
8759 if (const Type *T = NNS->getAsType())
8760 if (isa<TemplateSpecializationType>(T))
8761 return true;
8762
8763 return false;
8764}
8765
8766/// Make a dllexport or dllimport attr on a class template specialization take
8767/// effect.
8768static void dllExportImportClassTemplateSpecialization(
8769 Sema &S, ClassTemplateSpecializationDecl *Def) {
8770 auto *A = cast_or_null<InheritableAttr>(getDLLAttr(Def));
8771 assert(A && "dllExportImportClassTemplateSpecialization called "
8772 "on Def without dllexport or dllimport");
8773
8774 // We reject explicit instantiations in class scope, so there should
8775 // never be any delayed exported classes to worry about.
8776 assert(S.DelayedDllExportClasses.empty() &&
8777 "delayed exports present at explicit instantiation");
8778 S.checkClassLevelDLLAttribute(Def);
8779
8780 // Propagate attribute to base class templates.
8781 for (auto &B : Def->bases()) {
8782 if (auto *BT = dyn_cast_or_null<ClassTemplateSpecializationDecl>(
8783 B.getType()->getAsCXXRecordDecl()))
8784 S.propagateDLLAttrToBaseClassTemplate(Def, A, BT, B.getBeginLoc());
8785 }
8786
8787 S.referenceDLLExportedClassMethods();
8788}
8789
8790// Explicit instantiation of a class template specialization
8791DeclResult Sema::ActOnExplicitInstantiation(
8792 Scope *S, SourceLocation ExternLoc, SourceLocation TemplateLoc,
8793 unsigned TagSpec, SourceLocation KWLoc, const CXXScopeSpec &SS,
8794 TemplateTy TemplateD, SourceLocation TemplateNameLoc,
8795 SourceLocation LAngleLoc, ASTTemplateArgsPtr TemplateArgsIn,
8796 SourceLocation RAngleLoc, const ParsedAttributesView &Attr) {
8797 // Find the class template we're specializing
8798 TemplateName Name = TemplateD.get();
8799 TemplateDecl *TD = Name.getAsTemplateDecl();
8800 // Check that the specialization uses the same tag kind as the
8801 // original template.
8802 TagTypeKind Kind = TypeWithKeyword::getTagTypeKindForTypeSpec(TagSpec);
8803 assert(Kind != TTK_Enum &&
8804 "Invalid enum tag in class template explicit instantiation!");
8805
8806 ClassTemplateDecl *ClassTemplate = dyn_cast<ClassTemplateDecl>(TD);
8807
8808 if (!ClassTemplate) {
8809 NonTagKind NTK = getNonTagTypeDeclKind(TD, Kind);
8810 Diag(TemplateNameLoc, diag::err_tag_reference_non_tag) << TD << NTK << Kind;
8811 Diag(TD->getLocation(), diag::note_previous_use);
8812 return true;
8813 }
8814
8815 if (!isAcceptableTagRedeclaration(ClassTemplate->getTemplatedDecl(),
8816 Kind, /*isDefinition*/false, KWLoc,
8817 ClassTemplate->getIdentifier())) {
8818 Diag(KWLoc, diag::err_use_with_wrong_tag)
8819 << ClassTemplate
8820 << FixItHint::CreateReplacement(KWLoc,
8821 ClassTemplate->getTemplatedDecl()->getKindName());
8822 Diag(ClassTemplate->getTemplatedDecl()->getLocation(),
8823 diag::note_previous_use);
8824 Kind = ClassTemplate->getTemplatedDecl()->getTagKind();
8825 }
8826
8827 // C++0x [temp.explicit]p2:
8828 // There are two forms of explicit instantiation: an explicit instantiation
8829 // definition and an explicit instantiation declaration. An explicit
8830 // instantiation declaration begins with the extern keyword. [...]
8831 TemplateSpecializationKind TSK = ExternLoc.isInvalid()
8832 ? TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDefinition
8833 : TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDeclaration;
8834
8835 if (TSK == TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDeclaration &&
8836 !Context.getTargetInfo().getTriple().isWindowsGNUEnvironment()) {
8837 // Check for dllexport class template instantiation declarations,
8838 // except for MinGW mode.
8839 for (const ParsedAttr &AL : Attr) {
8840 if (AL.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_DLLExport) {
8841 Diag(ExternLoc,
8842 diag::warn_attribute_dllexport_explicit_instantiation_decl);
8843 Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::note_attribute);
8844 break;
8845 }
8846 }
8847
8848 if (auto *A = ClassTemplate->getTemplatedDecl()->getAttr<DLLExportAttr>()) {
8849 Diag(ExternLoc,
8850 diag::warn_attribute_dllexport_explicit_instantiation_decl);
8851 Diag(A->getLocation(), diag::note_attribute);
8852 }
8853 }
8854
8855 // In MSVC mode, dllimported explicit instantiation definitions are treated as
8856 // instantiation declarations for most purposes.
8857 bool DLLImportExplicitInstantiationDef = false;
8858 if (TSK == TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDefinition &&
8859 Context.getTargetInfo().getCXXABI().isMicrosoft()) {
8860 // Check for dllimport class template instantiation definitions.
8861 bool DLLImport =
8862 ClassTemplate->getTemplatedDecl()->getAttr<DLLImportAttr>();
8863 for (const ParsedAttr &AL : Attr) {
8864 if (AL.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_DLLImport)
8865 DLLImport = true;
8866 if (AL.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_DLLExport) {
8867 // dllexport trumps dllimport here.
8868 DLLImport = false;
8869 break;
8870 }
8871 }
8872 if (DLLImport) {
8873 TSK = TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDeclaration;
8874 DLLImportExplicitInstantiationDef = true;
8875 }
8876 }
8877
8878 // Translate the parser's template argument list in our AST format.
8879 TemplateArgumentListInfo TemplateArgs(LAngleLoc, RAngleLoc);
8880 translateTemplateArguments(TemplateArgsIn, TemplateArgs);
8881
8882 // Check that the template argument list is well-formed for this
8883 // template.
8884 SmallVector<TemplateArgument, 4> Converted;
8885 if (CheckTemplateArgumentList(ClassTemplate, TemplateNameLoc,
8886 TemplateArgs, false, Converted))
8887 return true;
8888
8889 // Find the class template specialization declaration that
8890 // corresponds to these arguments.
8891 void *InsertPos = nullptr;
8892 ClassTemplateSpecializationDecl *PrevDecl
8893 = ClassTemplate->findSpecialization(Converted, InsertPos);
8894
8895 TemplateSpecializationKind PrevDecl_TSK
8896 = PrevDecl ? PrevDecl->getTemplateSpecializationKind() : TSK_Undeclared;
8897
8898 if (TSK == TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDefinition && PrevDecl != nullptr &&
8899 Context.getTargetInfo().getTriple().isWindowsGNUEnvironment()) {
8900 // Check for dllexport class template instantiation definitions in MinGW
8901 // mode, if a previous declaration of the instantiation was seen.
8902 for (const ParsedAttr &AL : Attr) {
8903 if (AL.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_DLLExport) {
8904 Diag(AL.getLoc(),
8905 diag::warn_attribute_dllexport_explicit_instantiation_def);
8906 break;
8907 }
8908 }
8909 }
8910
8911 if (CheckExplicitInstantiation(*this, ClassTemplate, TemplateNameLoc,
8912 SS.isSet(), TSK))
8913 return true;
8914
8915 ClassTemplateSpecializationDecl *Specialization = nullptr;
8916
8917 bool HasNoEffect = false;
8918 if (PrevDecl) {
8919 if (CheckSpecializationInstantiationRedecl(TemplateNameLoc, TSK,
8920 PrevDecl, PrevDecl_TSK,
8921 PrevDecl->getPointOfInstantiation(),
8922 HasNoEffect))
8923 return PrevDecl;
8924
8925 // Even though HasNoEffect == true means that this explicit instantiation
8926 // has no effect on semantics, we go on to put its syntax in the AST.
8927
8928 if (PrevDecl_TSK == TSK_ImplicitInstantiation ||
8929 PrevDecl_TSK == TSK_Undeclared) {
8930 // Since the only prior class template specialization with these
8931 // arguments was referenced but not declared, reuse that
8932 // declaration node as our own, updating the source location
8933 // for the template name to reflect our new declaration.
8934 // (Other source locations will be updated later.)
8935 Specialization = PrevDecl;
8936 Specialization->setLocation(TemplateNameLoc);
8937 PrevDecl = nullptr;
8938 }
8939
8940 if (PrevDecl_TSK == TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDeclaration &&
8941 DLLImportExplicitInstantiationDef) {
8942 // The new specialization might add a dllimport attribute.
8943 HasNoEffect = false;
8944 }
8945 }
8946
8947 if (!Specialization) {
8948 // Create a new class template specialization declaration node for
8949 // this explicit specialization.
8950 Specialization
8951 = ClassTemplateSpecializationDecl::Create(Context, Kind,
8952 ClassTemplate->getDeclContext(),
8953 KWLoc, TemplateNameLoc,
8954 ClassTemplate,
8955 Converted,
8956 PrevDecl);
8957 SetNestedNameSpecifier(*this, Specialization, SS);
8958
8959 if (!HasNoEffect && !PrevDecl) {
8960 // Insert the new specialization.
8961 ClassTemplate->AddSpecialization(Specialization, InsertPos);
8962 }
8963 }
8964
8965 // Build the fully-sugared type for this explicit instantiation as
8966 // the user wrote in the explicit instantiation itself. This means
8967 // that we'll pretty-print the type retrieved from the
8968 // specialization's declaration the way that the user actually wrote
8969 // the explicit instantiation, rather than formatting the name based
8970 // on the "canonical" representation used to store the template
8971 // arguments in the specialization.
8972 TypeSourceInfo *WrittenTy
8973 = Context.getTemplateSpecializationTypeInfo(Name, TemplateNameLoc,
8974 TemplateArgs,
8975 Context.getTypeDeclType(Specialization));
8976 Specialization->setTypeAsWritten(WrittenTy);
8977
8978 // Set source locations for keywords.
8979 Specialization->setExternLoc(ExternLoc);
8980 Specialization->setTemplateKeywordLoc(TemplateLoc);
8981 Specialization->setBraceRange(SourceRange());
8982
8983 bool PreviouslyDLLExported = Specialization->hasAttr<DLLExportAttr>();
8984 ProcessDeclAttributeList(S, Specialization, Attr);
8985
8986 // Add the explicit instantiation into its lexical context. However,
8987 // since explicit instantiations are never found by name lookup, we
8988 // just put it into the declaration context directly.
8989 Specialization->setLexicalDeclContext(CurContext);
8990 CurContext->addDecl(Specialization);
8991
8992 // Syntax is now OK, so return if it has no other effect on semantics.
8993 if (HasNoEffect) {
8994 // Set the template specialization kind.
8995 Specialization->setTemplateSpecializationKind(TSK);
8996 return Specialization;
8997 }
8998
8999 // C++ [temp.explicit]p3:
9000 // A definition of a class template or class member template
9001 // shall be in scope at the point of the explicit instantiation of
9002 // the class template or class member template.
9003 //
9004 // This check comes when we actually try to perform the
9005 // instantiation.
9006 ClassTemplateSpecializationDecl *Def
9007 = cast_or_null<ClassTemplateSpecializationDecl>(
9008 Specialization->getDefinition());
9009 if (!Def)
9010 InstantiateClassTemplateSpecialization(TemplateNameLoc, Specialization, TSK);
9011 else if (TSK == TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDefinition) {
9012 MarkVTableUsed(TemplateNameLoc, Specialization, true);
9013 Specialization->setPointOfInstantiation(Def->getPointOfInstantiation());
9014 }
9015
9016 // Instantiate the members of this class template specialization.
9017 Def = cast_or_null<ClassTemplateSpecializationDecl>(
9018 Specialization->getDefinition());
9019 if (Def) {
9020 TemplateSpecializationKind Old_TSK = Def->getTemplateSpecializationKind();
9021 // Fix a TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDeclaration followed by a
9022 // TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDefinition
9023 if (Old_TSK == TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDeclaration &&
9024 (TSK == TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDefinition ||
9025 DLLImportExplicitInstantiationDef)) {
9026 // FIXME: Need to notify the ASTMutationListener that we did this.
9027 Def->setTemplateSpecializationKind(TSK);
9028
9029 if (!getDLLAttr(Def) && getDLLAttr(Specialization) &&
9030 (Context.getTargetInfo().getCXXABI().isMicrosoft() ||
9031 Context.getTargetInfo().getTriple().isWindowsItaniumEnvironment())) {
9032 // In the MS ABI, an explicit instantiation definition can add a dll
9033 // attribute to a template with a previous instantiation declaration.
9034 // MinGW doesn't allow this.
9035 auto *A = cast<InheritableAttr>(
9036 getDLLAttr(Specialization)->clone(getASTContext()));
9037 A->setInherited(true);
9038 Def->addAttr(A);
9039 dllExportImportClassTemplateSpecialization(*this, Def);
9040 }
9041 }
9042
9043 // Fix a TSK_ImplicitInstantiation followed by a
9044 // TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDefinition
9045 bool NewlyDLLExported =
9046 !PreviouslyDLLExported && Specialization->hasAttr<DLLExportAttr>();
9047 if (Old_TSK == TSK_ImplicitInstantiation && NewlyDLLExported &&
9048 (Context.getTargetInfo().getCXXABI().isMicrosoft() ||
9049 Context.getTargetInfo().getTriple().isWindowsItaniumEnvironment())) {
9050 // In the MS ABI, an explicit instantiation definition can add a dll
9051 // attribute to a template with a previous implicit instantiation.
9052 // MinGW doesn't allow this. We limit clang to only adding dllexport, to
9053 // avoid potentially strange codegen behavior. For example, if we extend
9054 // this conditional to dllimport, and we have a source file calling a
9055 // method on an implicitly instantiated template class instance and then
9056 // declaring a dllimport explicit instantiation definition for the same
9057 // template class, the codegen for the method call will not respect the
9058 // dllimport, while it will with cl. The Def will already have the DLL
9059 // attribute, since the Def and Specialization will be the same in the
9060 // case of Old_TSK == TSK_ImplicitInstantiation, and we already added the
9061 // attribute to the Specialization; we just need to make it take effect.
9062 assert(Def == Specialization &&
9063 "Def and Specialization should match for implicit instantiation");
9064 dllExportImportClassTemplateSpecialization(*this, Def);
9065 }
9066
9067 // In MinGW mode, export the template instantiation if the declaration
9068 // was marked dllexport.
9069 if (PrevDecl_TSK == TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDeclaration &&
9070 Context.getTargetInfo().getTriple().isWindowsGNUEnvironment() &&
9071 PrevDecl->hasAttr<DLLExportAttr>()) {
9072 dllExportImportClassTemplateSpecialization(*this, Def);
9073 }
9074
9075 // Set the template specialization kind. Make sure it is set before
9076 // instantiating the members which will trigger ASTConsumer callbacks.
9077 Specialization->setTemplateSpecializationKind(TSK);
9078 InstantiateClassTemplateSpecializationMembers(TemplateNameLoc, Def, TSK);
9079 } else {
9080
9081 // Set the template specialization kind.
9082 Specialization->setTemplateSpecializationKind(TSK);
9083 }
9084
9085 return Specialization;
9086}
9087
9088// Explicit instantiation of a member class of a class template.
9089DeclResult
9090Sema::ActOnExplicitInstantiation(Scope *S, SourceLocation ExternLoc,
9091 SourceLocation TemplateLoc, unsigned TagSpec,
9092 SourceLocation KWLoc, CXXScopeSpec &SS,
9093 IdentifierInfo *Name, SourceLocation NameLoc,
9094 const ParsedAttributesView &Attr) {
9095
9096 bool Owned = false;
9097 bool IsDependent = false;
9098 Decl *TagD = ActOnTag(S, TagSpec, Sema::TUK_Reference,
9099 KWLoc, SS, Name, NameLoc, Attr, AS_none,
9100 /*ModulePrivateLoc=*/SourceLocation(),
9101 MultiTemplateParamsArg(), Owned, IsDependent,
9102 SourceLocation(), false, TypeResult(),
9103 /*IsTypeSpecifier*/false,
9104 /*IsTemplateParamOrArg*/false);
9105 assert(!IsDependent && "explicit instantiation of dependent name not yet handled");
9106
9107 if (!TagD)
9108 return true;
9109
9110 TagDecl *Tag = cast<TagDecl>(TagD);
9111 assert(!Tag->isEnum() && "shouldn't see enumerations here");
9112
9113 if (Tag->isInvalidDecl())
9114 return true;
9115
9116 CXXRecordDecl *Record = cast<CXXRecordDecl>(Tag);
9117 CXXRecordDecl *Pattern = Record->getInstantiatedFromMemberClass();
9118 if (!Pattern) {
9119 Diag(TemplateLoc, diag::err_explicit_instantiation_nontemplate_type)
9120 << Context.getTypeDeclType(Record);
9121 Diag(Record->getLocation(), diag::note_nontemplate_decl_here);
9122 return true;
9123 }
9124
9125 // C++0x [temp.explicit]p2:
9126 // If the explicit instantiation is for a class or member class, the
9127 // elaborated-type-specifier in the declaration shall include a
9128 // simple-template-id.
9129 //
9130 // C++98 has the same restriction, just worded differently.
9131 if (!ScopeSpecifierHasTemplateId(SS))
9132 Diag(TemplateLoc, diag::ext_explicit_instantiation_without_qualified_id)
9133 << Record << SS.getRange();
9134
9135 // C++0x [temp.explicit]p2:
9136 // There are two forms of explicit instantiation: an explicit instantiation
9137 // definition and an explicit instantiation declaration. An explicit
9138 // instantiation declaration begins with the extern keyword. [...]
9139 TemplateSpecializationKind TSK
9140 = ExternLoc.isInvalid()? TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDefinition
9141 : TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDeclaration;
9142
9143 CheckExplicitInstantiation(*this, Record, NameLoc, true, TSK);
9144
9145 // Verify that it is okay to explicitly instantiate here.
9146 CXXRecordDecl *PrevDecl
9147 = cast_or_null<CXXRecordDecl>(Record->getPreviousDecl());
9148 if (!PrevDecl && Record->getDefinition())
9149 PrevDecl = Record;
9150 if (PrevDecl) {
9151 MemberSpecializationInfo *MSInfo = PrevDecl->getMemberSpecializationInfo();
9152 bool HasNoEffect = false;
9153 assert(MSInfo && "No member specialization information?");
9154 if (CheckSpecializationInstantiationRedecl(TemplateLoc, TSK,
9155 PrevDecl,
9156 MSInfo->getTemplateSpecializationKind(),
9157 MSInfo->getPointOfInstantiation(),
9158 HasNoEffect))
9159 return true;
9160 if (HasNoEffect)
9161 return TagD;
9162 }
9163
9164 CXXRecordDecl *RecordDef
9165 = cast_or_null<CXXRecordDecl>(Record->getDefinition());
9166 if (!RecordDef) {
9167 // C++ [temp.explicit]p3:
9168 // A definition of a member class of a class template shall be in scope
9169 // at the point of an explicit instantiation of the member class.
9170 CXXRecordDecl *Def
9171 = cast_or_null<CXXRecordDecl>(Pattern->getDefinition());
9172 if (!Def) {
9173 Diag(TemplateLoc, diag::err_explicit_instantiation_undefined_member)
9174 << 0 << Record->getDeclName() << Record->getDeclContext();
9175 Diag(Pattern->getLocation(), diag::note_forward_declaration)
9176 << Pattern;
9177 return true;
9178 } else {
9179 if (InstantiateClass(NameLoc, Record, Def,
9180 getTemplateInstantiationArgs(Record),
9181 TSK))
9182 return true;
9183
9184 RecordDef = cast_or_null<CXXRecordDecl>(Record->getDefinition());
9185 if (!RecordDef)
9186 return true;
9187 }
9188 }
9189
9190 // Instantiate all of the members of the class.
9191 InstantiateClassMembers(NameLoc, RecordDef,
9192 getTemplateInstantiationArgs(Record), TSK);
9193
9194 if (TSK == TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDefinition)
9195 MarkVTableUsed(NameLoc, RecordDef, true);
9196
9197 // FIXME: We don't have any representation for explicit instantiations of
9198 // member classes. Such a representation is not needed for compilation, but it
9199 // should be available for clients that want to see all of the declarations in
9200 // the source code.
9201 return TagD;
9202}
9203
9204DeclResult Sema::ActOnExplicitInstantiation(Scope *S,
9205 SourceLocation ExternLoc,
9206 SourceLocation TemplateLoc,
9207 Declarator &D) {
9208 // Explicit instantiations always require a name.
9209 // TODO: check if/when DNInfo should replace Name.
9210 DeclarationNameInfo NameInfo = GetNameForDeclarator(D);
9211 DeclarationName Name = NameInfo.getName();
9212 if (!Name) {
9213 if (!D.isInvalidType())
9214 Diag(D.getDeclSpec().getBeginLoc(),
9215 diag::err_explicit_instantiation_requires_name)
9216 << D.getDeclSpec().getSourceRange() << D.getSourceRange();
9217
9218 return true;
9219 }
9220
9221 // The scope passed in may not be a decl scope. Zip up the scope tree until
9222 // we find one that is.
9223 while ((S->getFlags() & Scope::DeclScope) == 0 ||
9224 (S->getFlags() & Scope::TemplateParamScope) != 0)
9225 S = S->getParent();
9226
9227 // Determine the type of the declaration.
9228 TypeSourceInfo *T = GetTypeForDeclarator(D, S);
9229 QualType R = T->getType();
9230 if (R.isNull())
9231 return true;
9232
9233 // C++ [dcl.stc]p1:
9234 // A storage-class-specifier shall not be specified in [...] an explicit
9235 // instantiation (14.7.2) directive.
9236 if (D.getDeclSpec().getStorageClassSpec() == DeclSpec::SCS_typedef) {
9237 Diag(D.getIdentifierLoc(), diag::err_explicit_instantiation_of_typedef)
9238 << Name;
9239 return true;
9240 } else if (D.getDeclSpec().getStorageClassSpec()
9241 != DeclSpec::SCS_unspecified) {
9242 // Complain about then remove the storage class specifier.
9243 Diag(D.getIdentifierLoc(), diag::err_explicit_instantiation_storage_class)
9244 << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(D.getDeclSpec().getStorageClassSpecLoc());
9245
9246 D.getMutableDeclSpec().ClearStorageClassSpecs();
9247 }
9248
9249 // C++0x [temp.explicit]p1:
9250 // [...] An explicit instantiation of a function template shall not use the
9251 // inline or constexpr specifiers.
9252 // Presumably, this also applies to member functions of class templates as
9253 // well.
9254 if (D.getDeclSpec().isInlineSpecified())
9255 Diag(D.getDeclSpec().getInlineSpecLoc(),
9256 getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 ?
9257 diag::err_explicit_instantiation_inline :
9258 diag::warn_explicit_instantiation_inline_0x)
9259 << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(D.getDeclSpec().getInlineSpecLoc());
9260 if (D.getDeclSpec().isConstexprSpecified() && R->isFunctionType())
9261 // FIXME: Add a fix-it to remove the 'constexpr' and add a 'const' if one is
9262 // not already specified.
9263 Diag(D.getDeclSpec().getConstexprSpecLoc(),
9264 diag::err_explicit_instantiation_constexpr);
9265
9266 // A deduction guide is not on the list of entities that can be explicitly
9267 // instantiated.
9268 if (Name.getNameKind() == DeclarationName::CXXDeductionGuideName) {
9269 Diag(D.getDeclSpec().getBeginLoc(), diag::err_deduction_guide_specialized)
9270 << /*explicit instantiation*/ 0;
9271 return true;
9272 }
9273
9274 // C++0x [temp.explicit]p2:
9275 // There are two forms of explicit instantiation: an explicit instantiation
9276 // definition and an explicit instantiation declaration. An explicit
9277 // instantiation declaration begins with the extern keyword. [...]
9278 TemplateSpecializationKind TSK
9279 = ExternLoc.isInvalid()? TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDefinition
9280 : TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDeclaration;
9281
9282 LookupResult Previous(*this, NameInfo, LookupOrdinaryName);
9283 LookupParsedName(Previous, S, &D.getCXXScopeSpec());
9284
9285 if (!R->isFunctionType()) {
9286 // C++ [temp.explicit]p1:
9287 // A [...] static data member of a class template can be explicitly
9288 // instantiated from the member definition associated with its class
9289 // template.
9290 // C++1y [temp.explicit]p1:
9291 // A [...] variable [...] template specialization can be explicitly
9292 // instantiated from its template.
9293 if (Previous.isAmbiguous())
9294 return true;
9295
9296 VarDecl *Prev = Previous.getAsSingle<VarDecl>();
9297 VarTemplateDecl *PrevTemplate = Previous.getAsSingle<VarTemplateDecl>();
9298
9299 if (!PrevTemplate) {
9300 if (!Prev || !Prev->isStaticDataMember()) {
9301 // We expect to see a static data member here.
9302 Diag(D.getIdentifierLoc(), diag::err_explicit_instantiation_not_known)
9303 << Name;
9304 for (LookupResult::iterator P = Previous.begin(), PEnd = Previous.end();
9305 P != PEnd; ++P)
9306 Diag((*P)->getLocation(), diag::note_explicit_instantiation_here);
9307 return true;
9308 }
9309
9310 if (!Prev->getInstantiatedFromStaticDataMember()) {
9311 // FIXME: Check for explicit specialization?
9312 Diag(D.getIdentifierLoc(),
9313 diag::err_explicit_instantiation_data_member_not_instantiated)
9314 << Prev;
9315 Diag(Prev->getLocation(), diag::note_explicit_instantiation_here);
9316 // FIXME: Can we provide a note showing where this was declared?
9317 return true;
9318 }
9319 } else {
9320 // Explicitly instantiate a variable template.
9321
9322 // C++1y [dcl.spec.auto]p6:
9323 // ... A program that uses auto or decltype(auto) in a context not
9324 // explicitly allowed in this section is ill-formed.
9325 //
9326 // This includes auto-typed variable template instantiations.
9327 if (R->isUndeducedType()) {
9328 Diag(T->getTypeLoc().getBeginLoc(),
9329 diag::err_auto_not_allowed_var_inst);
9330 return true;
9331 }
9332
9333 if (D.getName().getKind() != UnqualifiedIdKind::IK_TemplateId) {
9334 // C++1y [temp.explicit]p3:
9335 // If the explicit instantiation is for a variable, the unqualified-id
9336 // in the declaration shall be a template-id.
9337 Diag(D.getIdentifierLoc(),
9338 diag::err_explicit_instantiation_without_template_id)
9339 << PrevTemplate;
9340 Diag(PrevTemplate->getLocation(),
9341 diag::note_explicit_instantiation_here);
9342 return true;
9343 }
9344
9345 // Translate the parser's template argument list into our AST format.
9346 TemplateArgumentListInfo TemplateArgs =
9347 makeTemplateArgumentListInfo(*this, *D.getName().TemplateId);
9348
9349 DeclResult Res = CheckVarTemplateId(PrevTemplate, TemplateLoc,
9350 D.getIdentifierLoc(), TemplateArgs);
9351 if (Res.isInvalid())
9352 return true;
9353
9354 // Ignore access control bits, we don't need them for redeclaration
9355 // checking.
9356 Prev = cast<VarDecl>(Res.get());
9357 }
9358
9359 // C++0x [temp.explicit]p2:
9360 // If the explicit instantiation is for a member function, a member class
9361 // or a static data member of a class template specialization, the name of
9362 // the class template specialization in the qualified-id for the member
9363 // name shall be a simple-template-id.
9364 //
9365 // C++98 has the same restriction, just worded differently.
9366 //
9367 // This does not apply to variable template specializations, where the
9368 // template-id is in the unqualified-id instead.
9369 if (!ScopeSpecifierHasTemplateId(D.getCXXScopeSpec()) && !PrevTemplate)
9370 Diag(D.getIdentifierLoc(),
9371 diag::ext_explicit_instantiation_without_qualified_id)
9372 << Prev << D.getCXXScopeSpec().getRange();
9373
9374 CheckExplicitInstantiation(*this, Prev, D.getIdentifierLoc(), true, TSK);
9375
9376 // Verify that it is okay to explicitly instantiate here.
9377 TemplateSpecializationKind PrevTSK = Prev->getTemplateSpecializationKind();
9378 SourceLocation POI = Prev->getPointOfInstantiation();
9379 bool HasNoEffect = false;
9380 if (CheckSpecializationInstantiationRedecl(D.getIdentifierLoc(), TSK, Prev,
9381 PrevTSK, POI, HasNoEffect))
9382 return true;
9383
9384 if (!HasNoEffect) {
9385 // Instantiate static data member or variable template.
9386 Prev->setTemplateSpecializationKind(TSK, D.getIdentifierLoc());
9387 // Merge attributes.
9388 ProcessDeclAttributeList(S, Prev, D.getDeclSpec().getAttributes());
9389 if (TSK == TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDefinition)
9390 InstantiateVariableDefinition(D.getIdentifierLoc(), Prev);
9391 }
9392
9393 // Check the new variable specialization against the parsed input.
9394 if (PrevTemplate && Prev && !Context.hasSameType(Prev->getType(), R)) {
9395 Diag(T->getTypeLoc().getBeginLoc(),
9396 diag::err_invalid_var_template_spec_type)
9397 << 0 << PrevTemplate << R << Prev->getType();
9398 Diag(PrevTemplate->getLocation(), diag::note_template_declared_here)
9399 << 2 << PrevTemplate->getDeclName();
9400 return true;
9401 }
9402
9403 // FIXME: Create an ExplicitInstantiation node?
9404 return (Decl*) nullptr;
9405 }
9406
9407 // If the declarator is a template-id, translate the parser's template
9408 // argument list into our AST format.
9409 bool HasExplicitTemplateArgs = false;
9410 TemplateArgumentListInfo TemplateArgs;
9411 if (D.getName().getKind() == UnqualifiedIdKind::IK_TemplateId) {
9412 TemplateArgs = makeTemplateArgumentListInfo(*this, *D.getName().TemplateId);
9413 HasExplicitTemplateArgs = true;
9414 }
9415
9416 // C++ [temp.explicit]p1:
9417 // A [...] function [...] can be explicitly instantiated from its template.
9418 // A member function [...] of a class template can be explicitly
9419 // instantiated from the member definition associated with its class
9420 // template.
9421 UnresolvedSet<8> TemplateMatches;
9422 FunctionDecl *NonTemplateMatch = nullptr;
9423 TemplateSpecCandidateSet FailedCandidates(D.getIdentifierLoc());
9424 for (LookupResult::iterator P = Previous.begin(), PEnd = Previous.end();
9425 P != PEnd; ++P) {
9426 NamedDecl *Prev = *P;
9427 if (!HasExplicitTemplateArgs) {
9428 if (CXXMethodDecl *Method = dyn_cast<CXXMethodDecl>(Prev)) {
9429 QualType Adjusted = adjustCCAndNoReturn(R, Method->getType(),
9430 /*AdjustExceptionSpec*/true);
9431 if (Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(Method->getType(), Adjusted)) {
9432 if (Method->getPrimaryTemplate()) {
9433 TemplateMatches.addDecl(Method, P.getAccess());
9434 } else {
9435 // FIXME: Can this assert ever happen? Needs a test.
9436 assert(!NonTemplateMatch && "Multiple NonTemplateMatches");
9437 NonTemplateMatch = Method;
9438 }
9439 }
9440 }
9441 }
9442
9443 FunctionTemplateDecl *FunTmpl = dyn_cast<FunctionTemplateDecl>(Prev);
9444 if (!FunTmpl)
9445 continue;
9446
9447 TemplateDeductionInfo Info(FailedCandidates.getLocation());
9448 FunctionDecl *Specialization = nullptr;
9449 if (TemplateDeductionResult TDK
9450 = DeduceTemplateArguments(FunTmpl,
9451 (HasExplicitTemplateArgs ? &TemplateArgs
9452 : nullptr),
9453 R, Specialization, Info)) {
9454 // Keep track of almost-matches.
9455 FailedCandidates.addCandidate()
9456 .set(P.getPair(), FunTmpl->getTemplatedDecl(),
9457 MakeDeductionFailureInfo(Context, TDK, Info));
9458 (void)TDK;
9459 continue;
9460 }
9461
9462 // Target attributes are part of the cuda function signature, so
9463 // the cuda target of the instantiated function must match that of its
9464 // template. Given that C++ template deduction does not take
9465 // target attributes into account, we reject candidates here that
9466 // have a different target.
9467 if (LangOpts.CUDA &&
9468 IdentifyCUDATarget(Specialization,
9469 /* IgnoreImplicitHDAttributes = */ true) !=
9470 IdentifyCUDATarget(D.getDeclSpec().getAttributes())) {
9471 FailedCandidates.addCandidate().set(
9472 P.getPair(), FunTmpl->getTemplatedDecl(),
9473 MakeDeductionFailureInfo(Context, TDK_CUDATargetMismatch, Info));
9474 continue;
9475 }
9476
9477 TemplateMatches.addDecl(Specialization, P.getAccess());
9478 }
9479
9480 FunctionDecl *Specialization = NonTemplateMatch;
9481 if (!Specialization) {
9482 // Find the most specialized function template specialization.
9483 UnresolvedSetIterator Result = getMostSpecialized(
9484 TemplateMatches.begin(), TemplateMatches.end(), FailedCandidates,
9485 D.getIdentifierLoc(),
9486 PDiag(diag::err_explicit_instantiation_not_known) << Name,
9487 PDiag(diag::err_explicit_instantiation_ambiguous) << Name,
9488 PDiag(diag::note_explicit_instantiation_candidate));
9489
9490 if (Result == TemplateMatches.end())
9491 return true;
9492
9493 // Ignore access control bits, we don't need them for redeclaration checking.
9494 Specialization = cast<FunctionDecl>(*Result);
9495 }
9496
9497 // C++11 [except.spec]p4
9498 // In an explicit instantiation an exception-specification may be specified,
9499 // but is not required.
9500 // If an exception-specification is specified in an explicit instantiation
9501 // directive, it shall be compatible with the exception-specifications of
9502 // other declarations of that function.
9503 if (auto *FPT = R->getAs<FunctionProtoType>())
9504 if (FPT->hasExceptionSpec()) {
9505 unsigned DiagID =
9506 diag::err_mismatched_exception_spec_explicit_instantiation;
9507 if (getLangOpts().MicrosoftExt)
9508 DiagID = diag::ext_mismatched_exception_spec_explicit_instantiation;
9509 bool Result = CheckEquivalentExceptionSpec(
9510 PDiag(DiagID) << Specialization->getType(),
9511 PDiag(diag::note_explicit_instantiation_here),
9512 Specialization->getType()->getAs<FunctionProtoType>(),
9513 Specialization->getLocation(), FPT, D.getBeginLoc());
9514 // In Microsoft mode, mismatching exception specifications just cause a
9515 // warning.
9516 if (!getLangOpts().MicrosoftExt && Result)
9517 return true;
9518 }
9519
9520 if (Specialization->getTemplateSpecializationKind() == TSK_Undeclared) {
9521 Diag(D.getIdentifierLoc(),
9522 diag::err_explicit_instantiation_member_function_not_instantiated)
9523 << Specialization
9524 << (Specialization->getTemplateSpecializationKind() ==
9525 TSK_ExplicitSpecialization);
9526 Diag(Specialization->getLocation(), diag::note_explicit_instantiation_here);
9527 return true;
9528 }
9529
9530 FunctionDecl *PrevDecl = Specialization->getPreviousDecl();
9531 if (!PrevDecl && Specialization->isThisDeclarationADefinition())
9532 PrevDecl = Specialization;
9533
9534 if (PrevDecl) {
9535 bool HasNoEffect = false;
9536 if (CheckSpecializationInstantiationRedecl(D.getIdentifierLoc(), TSK,
9537 PrevDecl,
9538 PrevDecl->getTemplateSpecializationKind(),
9539 PrevDecl->getPointOfInstantiation(),
9540 HasNoEffect))
9541 return true;
9542
9543 // FIXME: We may still want to build some representation of this
9544 // explicit specialization.
9545 if (HasNoEffect)
9546 return (Decl*) nullptr;
9547 }
9548
9549 // HACK: libc++ has a bug where it attempts to explicitly instantiate the
9550 // functions
9551 // valarray<size_t>::valarray(size_t) and
9552 // valarray<size_t>::~valarray()
9553 // that it declared to have internal linkage with the internal_linkage
9554 // attribute. Ignore the explicit instantiation declaration in this case.
9555 if (Specialization->hasAttr<InternalLinkageAttr>() &&
9556 TSK == TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDeclaration) {
9557 if (auto *RD = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(Specialization->getDeclContext()))
9558 if (RD->getIdentifier() && RD->getIdentifier()->isStr("valarray") &&
9559 RD->isInStdNamespace())
9560 return (Decl*) nullptr;
9561 }
9562
9563 ProcessDeclAttributeList(S, Specialization, D.getDeclSpec().getAttributes());
9564
9565 // In MSVC mode, dllimported explicit instantiation definitions are treated as
9566 // instantiation declarations.
9567 if (TSK == TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDefinition &&
9568 Specialization->hasAttr<DLLImportAttr>() &&
9569 Context.getTargetInfo().getCXXABI().isMicrosoft())
9570 TSK = TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDeclaration;
9571
9572 Specialization->setTemplateSpecializationKind(TSK, D.getIdentifierLoc());
9573
9574 if (Specialization->isDefined()) {
9575 // Let the ASTConsumer know that this function has been explicitly
9576 // instantiated now, and its linkage might have changed.
9577 Consumer.HandleTopLevelDecl(DeclGroupRef(Specialization));
9578 } else if (TSK == TSK_ExplicitInstantiationDefinition)
9579 InstantiateFunctionDefinition(D.getIdentifierLoc(), Specialization);
9580
9581 // C++0x [temp.explicit]p2:
9582 // If the explicit instantiation is for a member function, a member class
9583 // or a static data member of a class template specialization, the name of
9584 // the class template specialization in the qualified-id for the member
9585 // name shall be a simple-template-id.
9586 //
9587 // C++98 has the same restriction, just worded differently.
9588 FunctionTemplateDecl *FunTmpl = Specialization->getPrimaryTemplate();
9589 if (D.getName().getKind() != UnqualifiedIdKind::IK_TemplateId && !FunTmpl &&
9590 D.getCXXScopeSpec().isSet() &&
9591 !ScopeSpecifierHasTemplateId(D.getCXXScopeSpec()))
9592 Diag(D.getIdentifierLoc(),
9593 diag::ext_explicit_instantiation_without_qualified_id)
9594 << Specialization << D.getCXXScopeSpec().getRange();
9595
9596 CheckExplicitInstantiation(
9597 *this,
9598 FunTmpl ? (NamedDecl *)FunTmpl
9599 : Specialization->getInstantiatedFromMemberFunction(),
9600 D.getIdentifierLoc(), D.getCXXScopeSpec().isSet(), TSK);
9601
9602 // FIXME: Create some kind of ExplicitInstantiationDecl here.
9603 return (Decl*) nullptr;
9604}
9605
9606TypeResult
9607Sema::ActOnDependentTag(Scope *S, unsigned TagSpec, TagUseKind TUK,
9608 const CXXScopeSpec &SS, IdentifierInfo *Name,
9609 SourceLocation TagLoc, SourceLocation NameLoc) {
9610 // This has to hold, because SS is expected to be defined.
9611 assert(Name && "Expected a name in a dependent tag");
9612
9613 NestedNameSpecifier *NNS = SS.getScopeRep();
9614 if (!NNS)
9615 return true;
9616
9617 TagTypeKind Kind = TypeWithKeyword::getTagTypeKindForTypeSpec(TagSpec);
9618
9619 if (TUK == TUK_Declaration || TUK == TUK_Definition) {
9620 Diag(NameLoc, diag::err_dependent_tag_decl)
9621 << (TUK == TUK_Definition) << Kind << SS.getRange();
9622 return true;
9623 }
9624
9625 // Create the resulting type.
9626 ElaboratedTypeKeyword Kwd = TypeWithKeyword::getKeywordForTagTypeKind(Kind);
9627 QualType Result = Context.getDependentNameType(Kwd, NNS, Name);
9628
9629 // Create type-source location information for this type.
9630 TypeLocBuilder TLB;
9631 DependentNameTypeLoc TL = TLB.push<DependentNameTypeLoc>(Result);
9632 TL.setElaboratedKeywordLoc(TagLoc);
9633 TL.setQualifierLoc(SS.getWithLocInContext(Context));
9634 TL.setNameLoc(NameLoc);
9635 return CreateParsedType(Result, TLB.getTypeSourceInfo(Context, Result));
9636}
9637
9638TypeResult
9639Sema::ActOnTypenameType(Scope *S, SourceLocation TypenameLoc,
9640 const CXXScopeSpec &SS, const IdentifierInfo &II,
9641 SourceLocation IdLoc) {
9642 if (SS.isInvalid())
9643 return true;
9644
9645 if (TypenameLoc.isValid() && S && !S->getTemplateParamParent())
9646 Diag(TypenameLoc,
9647 getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 ?
9648 diag::warn_cxx98_compat_typename_outside_of_template :
9649 diag::ext_typename_outside_of_template)
9650 << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(TypenameLoc);
9651
9652 NestedNameSpecifierLoc QualifierLoc = SS.getWithLocInContext(Context);
9653 QualType T = CheckTypenameType(TypenameLoc.isValid()? ETK_Typename : ETK_None,
9654 TypenameLoc, QualifierLoc, II, IdLoc);
9655 if (T.isNull())
9656 return true;
9657
9658 TypeSourceInfo *TSI = Context.CreateTypeSourceInfo(T);
9659 if (isa<DependentNameType>(T)) {
9660 DependentNameTypeLoc TL = TSI->getTypeLoc().castAs<DependentNameTypeLoc>();
9661 TL.setElaboratedKeywordLoc(TypenameLoc);
9662 TL.setQualifierLoc(QualifierLoc);
9663 TL.setNameLoc(IdLoc);
9664 } else {
9665 ElaboratedTypeLoc TL = TSI->getTypeLoc().castAs<ElaboratedTypeLoc>();
9666 TL.setElaboratedKeywordLoc(TypenameLoc);
9667 TL.setQualifierLoc(QualifierLoc);
9668 TL.getNamedTypeLoc().castAs<TypeSpecTypeLoc>().setNameLoc(IdLoc);
9669 }
9670
9671 return CreateParsedType(T, TSI);
9672}
9673
9674TypeResult
9675Sema::ActOnTypenameType(Scope *S,
9676 SourceLocation TypenameLoc,
9677 const CXXScopeSpec &SS,
9678 SourceLocation TemplateKWLoc,
9679 TemplateTy TemplateIn,
9680 IdentifierInfo *TemplateII,
9681 SourceLocation TemplateIILoc,
9682 SourceLocation LAngleLoc,
9683 ASTTemplateArgsPtr TemplateArgsIn,
9684 SourceLocation RAngleLoc) {
9685 if (TypenameLoc.isValid() && S && !S->getTemplateParamParent())
9686 Diag(TypenameLoc,
9687 getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 ?
9688 diag::warn_cxx98_compat_typename_outside_of_template :
9689 diag::ext_typename_outside_of_template)
9690 << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(TypenameLoc);
9691
9692 // Strangely, non-type results are not ignored by this lookup, so the
9693 // program is ill-formed if it finds an injected-class-name.
9694 if (TypenameLoc.isValid()) {
9695 auto *LookupRD =
9696 dyn_cast_or_null<CXXRecordDecl>(computeDeclContext(SS, false));
9697 if (LookupRD && LookupRD->getIdentifier() == TemplateII) {
9698 Diag(TemplateIILoc,
9699 diag::ext_out_of_line_qualified_id_type_names_constructor)
9700 << TemplateII << 0 /*injected-class-name used as template name*/
9701 << (TemplateKWLoc.isValid() ? 1 : 0 /*'template'/'typename' keyword*/);
9702 }
9703 }
9704
9705 // Translate the parser's template argument list in our AST format.
9706 TemplateArgumentListInfo TemplateArgs(LAngleLoc, RAngleLoc);
9707 translateTemplateArguments(TemplateArgsIn, TemplateArgs);
9708
9709 TemplateName Template = TemplateIn.get();
9710 if (DependentTemplateName *DTN = Template.getAsDependentTemplateName()) {
9711 // Construct a dependent template specialization type.
9712 assert(DTN && "dependent template has non-dependent name?");
9713 assert(DTN->getQualifier() == SS.getScopeRep());
9714 QualType T = Context.getDependentTemplateSpecializationType(ETK_Typename,
9715 DTN->getQualifier(),
9716 DTN->getIdentifier(),
9717 TemplateArgs);
9718
9719 // Create source-location information for this type.
9720 TypeLocBuilder Builder;
9721 DependentTemplateSpecializationTypeLoc SpecTL
9722 = Builder.push<DependentTemplateSpecializationTypeLoc>(T);
9723 SpecTL.setElaboratedKeywordLoc(TypenameLoc);
9724 SpecTL.setQualifierLoc(SS.getWithLocInContext(Context));
9725 SpecTL.setTemplateKeywordLoc(TemplateKWLoc);
9726 SpecTL.setTemplateNameLoc(TemplateIILoc);
9727 SpecTL.setLAngleLoc(LAngleLoc);
9728 SpecTL.setRAngleLoc(RAngleLoc);
9729 for (unsigned I = 0, N = TemplateArgs.size(); I != N; ++I)
9730 SpecTL.setArgLocInfo(I, TemplateArgs[I].getLocInfo());
9731 return CreateParsedType(T, Builder.getTypeSourceInfo(Context, T));
9732 }
9733
9734 QualType T = CheckTemplateIdType(Template, TemplateIILoc, TemplateArgs);
9735 if (T.isNull())
9736 return true;
9737
9738 // Provide source-location information for the template specialization type.
9739 TypeLocBuilder Builder;
9740 TemplateSpecializationTypeLoc SpecTL
9741 = Builder.push<TemplateSpecializationTypeLoc>(T);
9742 SpecTL.setTemplateKeywordLoc(TemplateKWLoc);
9743 SpecTL.setTemplateNameLoc(TemplateIILoc);
9744 SpecTL.setLAngleLoc(LAngleLoc);
9745 SpecTL.setRAngleLoc(RAngleLoc);
9746 for (unsigned I = 0, N = TemplateArgs.size(); I != N; ++I)
9747 SpecTL.setArgLocInfo(I, TemplateArgs[I].getLocInfo());
9748
9749 T = Context.getElaboratedType(ETK_Typename, SS.getScopeRep(), T);
9750 ElaboratedTypeLoc TL = Builder.push<ElaboratedTypeLoc>(T);
9751 TL.setElaboratedKeywordLoc(TypenameLoc);
9752 TL.setQualifierLoc(SS.getWithLocInContext(Context));
9753
9754 TypeSourceInfo *TSI = Builder.getTypeSourceInfo(Context, T);
9755 return CreateParsedType(T, TSI);
9756}
9757
9758
9759/// Determine whether this failed name lookup should be treated as being
9760/// disabled by a usage of std::enable_if.
9761static bool isEnableIf(NestedNameSpecifierLoc NNS, const IdentifierInfo &II,
9762 SourceRange &CondRange, Expr *&Cond) {
9763 // We must be looking for a ::type...
9764 if (!II.isStr("type"))
9765 return false;
9766
9767 // ... within an explicitly-written template specialization...
9768 if (!NNS || !NNS.getNestedNameSpecifier()->getAsType())
9769 return false;
9770 TypeLoc EnableIfTy = NNS.getTypeLoc();
9771 TemplateSpecializationTypeLoc EnableIfTSTLoc =
9772 EnableIfTy.getAs<TemplateSpecializationTypeLoc>();
9773 if (!EnableIfTSTLoc || EnableIfTSTLoc.getNumArgs() == 0)
9774 return false;
9775 const TemplateSpecializationType *EnableIfTST = EnableIfTSTLoc.getTypePtr();
9776
9777 // ... which names a complete class template declaration...
9778 const TemplateDecl *EnableIfDecl =
9779 EnableIfTST->getTemplateName().getAsTemplateDecl();
9780 if (!EnableIfDecl || EnableIfTST->isIncompleteType())
9781 return false;
9782
9783 // ... called "enable_if".
9784 const IdentifierInfo *EnableIfII =
9785 EnableIfDecl->getDeclName().getAsIdentifierInfo();
9786 if (!EnableIfII || !EnableIfII->isStr("enable_if"))
9787 return false;
9788
9789 // Assume the first template argument is the condition.
9790 CondRange = EnableIfTSTLoc.getArgLoc(0).getSourceRange();
9791
9792 // Dig out the condition.
9793 Cond = nullptr;
9794 if (EnableIfTSTLoc.getArgLoc(0).getArgument().getKind()
9795 != TemplateArgument::Expression)
9796 return true;
9797
9798 Cond = EnableIfTSTLoc.getArgLoc(0).getSourceExpression();
9799
9800 // Ignore Boolean literals; they add no value.
9801 if (isa<CXXBoolLiteralExpr>(Cond->IgnoreParenCasts()))
9802 Cond = nullptr;
9803
9804 return true;
9805}
9806
9807/// Build the type that describes a C++ typename specifier,
9808/// e.g., "typename T::type".
9809QualType
9810Sema::CheckTypenameType(ElaboratedTypeKeyword Keyword,
9811 SourceLocation KeywordLoc,
9812 NestedNameSpecifierLoc QualifierLoc,
9813 const IdentifierInfo &II,
9814 SourceLocation IILoc) {
9815 CXXScopeSpec SS;
9816 SS.Adopt(QualifierLoc);
9817
9818 DeclContext *Ctx = computeDeclContext(SS);
9819 if (!Ctx) {
9820 // If the nested-name-specifier is dependent and couldn't be
9821 // resolved to a type, build a typename type.
9822 assert(QualifierLoc.getNestedNameSpecifier()->isDependent());
9823 return Context.getDependentNameType(Keyword,
9824 QualifierLoc.getNestedNameSpecifier(),
9825 &II);
9826 }
9827
9828 // If the nested-name-specifier refers to the current instantiation,
9829 // the "typename" keyword itself is superfluous. In C++03, the
9830 // program is actually ill-formed. However, DR 382 (in C++0x CD1)
9831 // allows such extraneous "typename" keywords, and we retroactively
9832 // apply this DR to C++03 code with only a warning. In any case we continue.
9833
9834 if (RequireCompleteDeclContext(SS, Ctx))
9835 return QualType();
9836
9837 DeclarationName Name(&II);
9838 LookupResult Result(*this, Name, IILoc, LookupOrdinaryName);
9839 LookupQualifiedName(Result, Ctx, SS);
9840 unsigned DiagID = 0;
9841 Decl *Referenced = nullptr;
9842 switch (Result.getResultKind()) {
9843 case LookupResult::NotFound: {
9844 // If we're looking up 'type' within a template named 'enable_if', produce
9845 // a more specific diagnostic.
9846 SourceRange CondRange;
9847 Expr *Cond = nullptr;
9848 if (isEnableIf(QualifierLoc, II, CondRange, Cond)) {
9849 // If we have a condition, narrow it down to the specific failed
9850 // condition.
9851 if (Cond) {
9852 Expr *FailedCond;
9853 std::string FailedDescription;
9854 std::tie(FailedCond, FailedDescription) =
9855 findFailedBooleanCondition(Cond);
9856
9857 Diag(FailedCond->getExprLoc(),
9858 diag::err_typename_nested_not_found_requirement)
9859 << FailedDescription
9860 << FailedCond->getSourceRange();
9861 return QualType();
9862 }
9863
9864 Diag(CondRange.getBegin(), diag::err_typename_nested_not_found_enable_if)
9865 << Ctx << CondRange;
9866 return QualType();
9867 }
9868
9869 DiagID = diag::err_typename_nested_not_found;
9870 break;
9871 }
9872
9873 case LookupResult::FoundUnresolvedValue: {
9874 // We found a using declaration that is a value. Most likely, the using
9875 // declaration itself is meant to have the 'typename' keyword.
9876 SourceRange FullRange(KeywordLoc.isValid() ? KeywordLoc : SS.getBeginLoc(),
9877 IILoc);
9878 Diag(IILoc, diag::err_typename_refers_to_using_value_decl)
9879 << Name << Ctx << FullRange;
9880 if (UnresolvedUsingValueDecl *Using
9881 = dyn_cast<UnresolvedUsingValueDecl>(Result.getRepresentativeDecl())){
9882 SourceLocation Loc = Using->getQualifierLoc().getBeginLoc();
9883 Diag(Loc, diag::note_using_value_decl_missing_typename)
9884 << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(Loc, "typename ");
9885 }
9886 }
9887 // Fall through to create a dependent typename type, from which we can recover
9888 // better.
9889 LLVM_FALLTHROUGH;
9890
9891 case LookupResult::NotFoundInCurrentInstantiation:
9892 // Okay, it's a member of an unknown instantiation.
9893 return Context.getDependentNameType(Keyword,
9894 QualifierLoc.getNestedNameSpecifier(),
9895 &II);
9896
9897 case LookupResult::Found:
9898 if (TypeDecl *Type = dyn_cast<TypeDecl>(Result.getFoundDecl())) {
9899 // C++ [class.qual]p2:
9900 // In a lookup in which function names are not ignored and the
9901 // nested-name-specifier nominates a class C, if the name specified
9902 // after the nested-name-specifier, when looked up in C, is the
9903 // injected-class-name of C [...] then the name is instead considered
9904 // to name the constructor of class C.
9905 //
9906 // Unlike in an elaborated-type-specifier, function names are not ignored
9907 // in typename-specifier lookup. However, they are ignored in all the
9908 // contexts where we form a typename type with no keyword (that is, in
9909 // mem-initializer-ids, base-specifiers, and elaborated-type-specifiers).
9910 //
9911 // FIXME: That's not strictly true: mem-initializer-id lookup does not
9912 // ignore functions, but that appears to be an oversight.
9913 auto *LookupRD = dyn_cast_or_null<CXXRecordDecl>(Ctx);
9914 auto *FoundRD = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(Type);
9915 if (Keyword == ETK_Typename && LookupRD && FoundRD &&
9916 FoundRD->isInjectedClassName() &&
9917 declaresSameEntity(LookupRD, cast<Decl>(FoundRD->getParent())))
9918 Diag(IILoc, diag::ext_out_of_line_qualified_id_type_names_constructor)
9919 << &II << 1 << 0 /*'typename' keyword used*/;
9920
9921 // We found a type. Build an ElaboratedType, since the
9922 // typename-specifier was just sugar.
9923 MarkAnyDeclReferenced(Type->getLocation(), Type, /*OdrUse=*/false);
9924 return Context.getElaboratedType(Keyword,
9925 QualifierLoc.getNestedNameSpecifier(),
9926 Context.getTypeDeclType(Type));
9927 }
9928
9929 // C++ [dcl.type.simple]p2:
9930 // A type-specifier of the form
9931 // typename[opt] nested-name-specifier[opt] template-name
9932 // is a placeholder for a deduced class type [...].
9933 if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus17) {
9934 if (auto *TD = getAsTypeTemplateDecl(Result.getFoundDecl())) {
9935 return Context.getElaboratedType(
9936 Keyword, QualifierLoc.getNestedNameSpecifier(),
9937 Context.getDeducedTemplateSpecializationType(TemplateName(TD),
9938 QualType(), false));
9939 }
9940 }
9941
9942 DiagID = diag::err_typename_nested_not_type;
9943 Referenced = Result.getFoundDecl();
9944 break;
9945
9946 case LookupResult::FoundOverloaded:
9947 DiagID = diag::err_typename_nested_not_type;
9948 Referenced = *Result.begin();
9949 break;
9950
9951 case LookupResult::Ambiguous:
9952 return QualType();
9953 }
9954
9955 // If we get here, it's because name lookup did not find a
9956 // type. Emit an appropriate diagnostic and return an error.
9957 SourceRange FullRange(KeywordLoc.isValid() ? KeywordLoc : SS.getBeginLoc(),
9958 IILoc);
9959 Diag(IILoc, DiagID) << FullRange << Name << Ctx;
9960 if (Referenced)
9961 Diag(Referenced->getLocation(), diag::note_typename_refers_here)
9962 << Name;
9963 return QualType();
9964}
9965
9966namespace {
9967 // See Sema::RebuildTypeInCurrentInstantiation
9968 class CurrentInstantiationRebuilder
9969 : public TreeTransform<CurrentInstantiationRebuilder> {
9970 SourceLocation Loc;
9971 DeclarationName Entity;
9972
9973 public:
9974 typedef TreeTransform<CurrentInstantiationRebuilder> inherited;
9975
9976 CurrentInstantiationRebuilder(Sema &SemaRef,
9977 SourceLocation Loc,
9978 DeclarationName Entity)
9979 : TreeTransform<CurrentInstantiationRebuilder>(SemaRef),
9980 Loc(Loc), Entity(Entity) { }
9981
9982 /// Determine whether the given type \p T has already been
9983 /// transformed.
9984 ///
9985 /// For the purposes of type reconstruction, a type has already been
9986 /// transformed if it is NULL or if it is not dependent.
9987 bool AlreadyTransformed(QualType T) {
9988 return T.isNull() || !T->isDependentType();
9989 }
9990
9991 /// Returns the location of the entity whose type is being
9992 /// rebuilt.
9993 SourceLocation getBaseLocation() { return Loc; }
9994
9995 /// Returns the name of the entity whose type is being rebuilt.
9996 DeclarationName getBaseEntity() { return Entity; }
9997
9998 /// Sets the "base" location and entity when that
9999 /// information is known based on another transformation.
10000 void setBase(SourceLocation Loc, DeclarationName Entity) {
10001 this->Loc = Loc;
10002 this->Entity = Entity;
10003 }
10004
10005 ExprResult TransformLambdaExpr(LambdaExpr *E) {
10006 // Lambdas never need to be transformed.
10007 return E;
10008 }
10009 };
10010} // end anonymous namespace
10011
10012/// Rebuilds a type within the context of the current instantiation.
10013///
10014/// The type \p T is part of the type of an out-of-line member definition of
10015/// a class template (or class template partial specialization) that was parsed
10016/// and constructed before we entered the scope of the class template (or
10017/// partial specialization thereof). This routine will rebuild that type now
10018/// that we have entered the declarator's scope, which may produce different
10019/// canonical types, e.g.,
10020///
10021/// \code
10022/// template<typename T>
10023/// struct X {
10024/// typedef T* pointer;
10025/// pointer data();
10026/// };
10027///
10028/// template<typename T>
10029/// typename X<T>::pointer X<T>::data() { ... }
10030/// \endcode
10031///
10032/// Here, the type "typename X<T>::pointer" will be created as a DependentNameType,
10033/// since we do not know that we can look into X<T> when we parsed the type.
10034/// This function will rebuild the type, performing the lookup of "pointer"
10035/// in X<T> and returning an ElaboratedType whose canonical type is the same
10036/// as the canonical type of T*, allowing the return types of the out-of-line
10037/// definition and the declaration to match.
10038TypeSourceInfo *Sema::RebuildTypeInCurrentInstantiation(TypeSourceInfo *T,
10039 SourceLocation Loc,
10040 DeclarationName Name) {
10041 if (!T || !T->getType()->isDependentType())
10042 return T;
10043
10044 CurrentInstantiationRebuilder Rebuilder(*this, Loc, Name);
10045 return Rebuilder.TransformType(T);
10046}
10047
10048ExprResult Sema::RebuildExprInCurrentInstantiation(Expr *E) {
10049 CurrentInstantiationRebuilder Rebuilder(*this, E->getExprLoc(),
10050 DeclarationName());
10051 return Rebuilder.TransformExpr(E);
10052}
10053
10054bool Sema::RebuildNestedNameSpecifierInCurrentInstantiation(CXXScopeSpec &SS) {
10055 if (SS.isInvalid())
10056 return true;
10057
10058 NestedNameSpecifierLoc QualifierLoc = SS.getWithLocInContext(Context);
10059 CurrentInstantiationRebuilder Rebuilder(*this, SS.getRange().getBegin(),
10060 DeclarationName());
10061 NestedNameSpecifierLoc Rebuilt
10062 = Rebuilder.TransformNestedNameSpecifierLoc(QualifierLoc);
10063 if (!Rebuilt)
10064 return true;
10065
10066 SS.Adopt(Rebuilt);
10067 return false;
10068}
10069
10070/// Rebuild the template parameters now that we know we're in a current
10071/// instantiation.
10072bool Sema::RebuildTemplateParamsInCurrentInstantiation(
10073 TemplateParameterList *Params) {
10074 for (unsigned I = 0, N = Params->size(); I != N; ++I) {
10075 Decl *Param = Params->getParam(I);
10076
10077 // There is nothing to rebuild in a type parameter.
10078 if (isa<TemplateTypeParmDecl>(Param))
10079 continue;
10080
10081 // Rebuild the template parameter list of a template template parameter.
10082 if (TemplateTemplateParmDecl *TTP
10083 = dyn_cast<TemplateTemplateParmDecl>(Param)) {
10084 if (RebuildTemplateParamsInCurrentInstantiation(
10085 TTP->getTemplateParameters()))
10086 return true;
10087
10088 continue;
10089 }
10090
10091 // Rebuild the type of a non-type template parameter.
10092 NonTypeTemplateParmDecl *NTTP = cast<NonTypeTemplateParmDecl>(Param);
10093 TypeSourceInfo *NewTSI
10094 = RebuildTypeInCurrentInstantiation(NTTP->getTypeSourceInfo(),
10095 NTTP->getLocation(),
10096 NTTP->getDeclName());
10097 if (!NewTSI)
10098 return true;
10099
10100 if (NewTSI->getType()->isUndeducedType()) {
10101 // C++17 [temp.dep.expr]p3:
10102 // An id-expression is type-dependent if it contains
10103 // - an identifier associated by name lookup with a non-type
10104 // template-parameter declared with a type that contains a
10105 // placeholder type (7.1.7.4),
10106 NewTSI = SubstAutoTypeSourceInfo(NewTSI, Context.DependentTy);
10107 }
10108
10109 if (NewTSI != NTTP->getTypeSourceInfo()) {
10110 NTTP->setTypeSourceInfo(NewTSI);
10111 NTTP->setType(NewTSI->getType());
10112 }
10113 }
10114
10115 return false;
10116}
10117
10118/// Produces a formatted string that describes the binding of
10119/// template parameters to template arguments.
10120std::string
10121Sema::getTemplateArgumentBindingsText(const TemplateParameterList *Params,
10122 const TemplateArgumentList &Args) {
10123 return getTemplateArgumentBindingsText(Params, Args.data(), Args.size());
10124}
10125
10126std::string
10127Sema::getTemplateArgumentBindingsText(const TemplateParameterList *Params,
10128 const TemplateArgument *Args,
10129 unsigned NumArgs) {
10130 SmallString<128> Str;
10131 llvm::raw_svector_ostream Out(Str);
10132
10133 if (!Params || Params->size() == 0 || NumArgs == 0)
10134 return std::string();
10135
10136 for (unsigned I = 0, N = Params->size(); I != N; ++I) {
10137 if (I >= NumArgs)
10138 break;
10139
10140 if (I == 0)
10141 Out << "[with ";
10142 else
10143 Out << ", ";
10144
10145 if (const IdentifierInfo *Id = Params->getParam(I)->getIdentifier()) {
10146 Out << Id->getName();
10147 } else {
10148 Out << '$' << I;
10149 }
10150
10151 Out << " = ";
10152 Args[I].print(getPrintingPolicy(), Out);
10153 }
10154
10155 Out << ']';
10156 return Out.str();
10157}
10158
10159void Sema::MarkAsLateParsedTemplate(FunctionDecl *FD, Decl *FnD,
10160 CachedTokens &Toks) {
10161 if (!FD)
10162 return;
10163
10164 auto LPT = llvm::make_unique<LateParsedTemplate>();
10165
10166 // Take tokens to avoid allocations
10167 LPT->Toks.swap(Toks);
10168 LPT->D = FnD;
10169 LateParsedTemplateMap.insert(std::make_pair(FD, std::move(LPT)));
10170
10171 FD->setLateTemplateParsed(true);
10172}
10173
10174void Sema::UnmarkAsLateParsedTemplate(FunctionDecl *FD) {
10175 if (!FD)
10176 return;
10177 FD->setLateTemplateParsed(false);
10178}
10179
10180bool Sema::IsInsideALocalClassWithinATemplateFunction() {
10181 DeclContext *DC = CurContext;
10182
10183 while (DC) {
10184 if (CXXRecordDecl *RD = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(CurContext)) {
10185 const FunctionDecl *FD = RD->isLocalClass();
10186 return (FD && FD->getTemplatedKind() != FunctionDecl::TK_NonTemplate);
10187 } else if (DC->isTranslationUnit() || DC->isNamespace())
10188 return false;
10189
10190 DC = DC->getParent();
10191 }
10192 return false;
10193}
10194
10195namespace {
10196/// Walk the path from which a declaration was instantiated, and check
10197/// that every explicit specialization along that path is visible. This enforces
10198/// C++ [temp.expl.spec]/6:
10199///
10200/// If a template, a member template or a member of a class template is
10201/// explicitly specialized then that specialization shall be declared before
10202/// the first use of that specialization that would cause an implicit
10203/// instantiation to take place, in every translation unit in which such a
10204/// use occurs; no diagnostic is required.
10205///
10206/// and also C++ [temp.class.spec]/1:
10207///
10208/// A partial specialization shall be declared before the first use of a
10209/// class template specialization that would make use of the partial
10210/// specialization as the result of an implicit or explicit instantiation
10211/// in every translation unit in which such a use occurs; no diagnostic is
10212/// required.
10213class ExplicitSpecializationVisibilityChecker {
10214 Sema &S;
10215 SourceLocation Loc;
10216 llvm::SmallVector<Module *, 8> Modules;
10217
10218public:
10219 ExplicitSpecializationVisibilityChecker(Sema &S, SourceLocation Loc)
10220 : S(S), Loc(Loc) {}
10221
10222 void check(NamedDecl *ND) {
10223 if (auto *FD = dyn_cast<FunctionDecl>(ND))
10224 return checkImpl(FD);
10225 if (auto *RD = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(ND))
10226 return checkImpl(RD);
10227 if (auto *VD = dyn_cast<VarDecl>(ND))
10228 return checkImpl(VD);
10229 if (auto *ED = dyn_cast<EnumDecl>(ND))
10230 return checkImpl(ED);
10231 }
10232
10233private:
10234 void diagnose(NamedDecl *D, bool IsPartialSpec) {
10235 auto Kind = IsPartialSpec ? Sema::MissingImportKind::PartialSpecialization
10236 : Sema::MissingImportKind::ExplicitSpecialization;
10237 const bool Recover = true;
10238
10239 // If we got a custom set of modules (because only a subset of the
10240 // declarations are interesting), use them, otherwise let
10241 // diagnoseMissingImport intelligently pick some.
10242 if (Modules.empty())
10243 S.diagnoseMissingImport(Loc, D, Kind, Recover);
10244 else
10245 S.diagnoseMissingImport(Loc, D, D->getLocation(), Modules, Kind, Recover);
10246 }
10247
10248 // Check a specific declaration. There are three problematic cases:
10249 //
10250 // 1) The declaration is an explicit specialization of a template
10251 // specialization.
10252 // 2) The declaration is an explicit specialization of a member of an
10253 // templated class.
10254 // 3) The declaration is an instantiation of a template, and that template
10255 // is an explicit specialization of a member of a templated class.
10256 //
10257 // We don't need to go any deeper than that, as the instantiation of the
10258 // surrounding class / etc is not triggered by whatever triggered this
10259 // instantiation, and thus should be checked elsewhere.
10260 template<typename SpecDecl>
10261 void checkImpl(SpecDecl *Spec) {
10262 bool IsHiddenExplicitSpecialization = false;
10263 if (Spec->getTemplateSpecializationKind() == TSK_ExplicitSpecialization) {
10264 IsHiddenExplicitSpecialization =
10265 Spec->getMemberSpecializationInfo()
10266 ? !S.hasVisibleMemberSpecialization(Spec, &Modules)
10267 : !S.hasVisibleExplicitSpecialization(Spec, &Modules);
10268 } else {
10269 checkInstantiated(Spec);
10270 }
10271
10272 if (IsHiddenExplicitSpecialization)
10273 diagnose(Spec->getMostRecentDecl(), false);
10274 }
10275
10276 void checkInstantiated(FunctionDecl *FD) {
10277 if (auto *TD = FD->getPrimaryTemplate())
10278 checkTemplate(TD);
10279 }
10280
10281 void checkInstantiated(CXXRecordDecl *RD) {
10282 auto *SD = dyn_cast<ClassTemplateSpecializationDecl>(RD);
10283 if (!SD)
10284 return;
10285
10286 auto From = SD->getSpecializedTemplateOrPartial();
10287 if (auto *TD = From.dyn_cast<ClassTemplateDecl *>())
10288 checkTemplate(TD);
10289 else if (auto *TD =
10290 From.dyn_cast<ClassTemplatePartialSpecializationDecl *>()) {
10291 if (!S.hasVisibleDeclaration(TD))
10292 diagnose(TD, true);
10293 checkTemplate(TD);
10294 }
10295 }
10296
10297 void checkInstantiated(VarDecl *RD) {
10298 auto *SD = dyn_cast<VarTemplateSpecializationDecl>(RD);
10299 if (!SD)
10300 return;
10301
10302 auto From = SD->getSpecializedTemplateOrPartial();
10303 if (auto *TD = From.dyn_cast<VarTemplateDecl *>())
10304 checkTemplate(TD);
10305 else if (auto *TD =
10306 From.dyn_cast<VarTemplatePartialSpecializationDecl *>()) {
10307 if (!S.hasVisibleDeclaration(TD))
10308 diagnose(TD, true);
10309 checkTemplate(TD);
10310 }
10311 }
10312
10313 void checkInstantiated(EnumDecl *FD) {}
10314
10315 template<typename TemplDecl>
10316 void checkTemplate(TemplDecl *TD) {
10317 if (TD->isMemberSpecialization()) {
10318 if (!S.hasVisibleMemberSpecialization(TD, &Modules))
10319 diagnose(TD->getMostRecentDecl(), false);
10320 }
10321 }
10322};
10323} // end anonymous namespace
10324
10325void Sema::checkSpecializationVisibility(SourceLocation Loc, NamedDecl *Spec) {
10326 if (!getLangOpts().Modules)
10327 return;
10328
10329 ExplicitSpecializationVisibilityChecker(*this, Loc).check(Spec);
10330}
10331
10332/// Check whether a template partial specialization that we've discovered
10333/// is hidden, and produce suitable diagnostics if so.
10334void Sema::checkPartialSpecializationVisibility(SourceLocation Loc,
10335 NamedDecl *Spec) {
10336 llvm::SmallVector<Module *, 8> Modules;
10337 if (!hasVisibleDeclaration(Spec, &Modules))
10338 diagnoseMissingImport(Loc, Spec, Spec->getLocation(), Modules,
10339 MissingImportKind::PartialSpecialization,
10340 /*Recover*/true);
10341}
